Not him but when I see dubs I feel a compulsion to reply. I think of anthros as people who are a little bit animalistic, a little bit beastly. I don't think of them as beasts pretending to be people. I think that in a story it is perfectly okay, and can even be cute and funny, if the wolf girl howls in the shower and thinks no one can hear her. It can be funny if the fox girl goes to bars and bets guys fifty dollars that she can eat fifty hard boiled eggs. It can be an amusing running gag if the catgirl is startled by cucumbers. But writing the character as being so much a slave to her instincts that she barely even has free will, that's not cute or funny any more. That's depressing. I don't like depressing. I speak for no one but myself, of course.

Molly loremaster here, she was never initially approached as a serious character so take this with a grain of salt. I’m a big fan of the concept of the animal stereotypes existing, but being mainly sourced in culture or entirely false. Like her family being vegetarian, but in my anthro world there’s no biological thing forcing herbivores to be herbivores, it’s more cultural. A cultural norm she bucks. Jokes aside, Molly’s canon is she’s single and infatuated with the idea of a monogamous relationship with a human man, but comes on too strong. I’ve toyed with the idea of her having a single love interest who is entirely oblivious. But that’s as far as her canon, and maybe I’m entirely off the point here now lol.
